From: OctaneOS <octaneos@local>
Date: Sat, 12 Jul 2026 00:00:00 +0000
Subject: [PATCH] input: xpad: skip LED identify for 8BitDo controllers

8BitDo controllers masquerade as the Microsoft X-Box 360 pad (045e:028e),
causing xpad to treat them as XTYPE_XBOX360 and fire the LED identify
command 2 seconds after connect. 8BitDo NAKs this command indefinitely
(it does not implement the Xbox 360 LED protocol). The BSP added a 5-second
watchdog that kills the pending URB to stop the NAK flood, but usb_kill_urb
causes the 8BitDo to disconnect and reconnect — triggering the cycle again.

Fix: detect 8BitDo by manufacturer string in xpad_led_probe and return
early, skipping LED setup entirely. This is safe because 8BitDo controllers
enumerate correctly without LED management; they just need input events.

Signed-off-by: OctaneOS <octaneos@local>
---
 drivers/input/joystick/xpad.c | 7 +++++++
 1 file changed, 7 insertions(+)

diff --git a/drivers/input/joystick/xpad.c b/drivers/input/joystick/xpad.c
--- a/drivers/input/joystick/xpad.c
+++ b/drivers/input/joystick/xpad.c
@@ -1762,6 +1762,13 @@ static int xpad_led_probe(struct usb_xpad *xpad)
 	if (xpad->xtype != XTYPE_XBOX360 && xpad->xtype != XTYPE_XBOX360W)
 		return 0;

+	/* 8BitDo controllers masquerade as 045e:028e (Xbox 360) but NAK the
+	 * LED identify command. The URB kill in irq_out_cancel_work causes them
+	 * to disconnect. Skip LED setup entirely for 8BitDo controllers. */
+	if (xpad->udev->manufacturer &&
+	    strstr(xpad->udev->manufacturer, "8BitDo"))
+		return 0;
+
 	xpad->led = led = kzalloc(sizeof(struct xpad_led), GFP_KERNEL);
 	if (!led)
 		return -ENOMEM;
